{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493259"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T07:02:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1270"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1270"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.55,0.21,0.06,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108076"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1270","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1270"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1270"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1887"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2778"},{"type":"tags","id":"3752"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11010"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33782"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39968"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44266"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108076"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 60-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of fatigue and numbness in her feet. She also reports constipation and difficulty concentrating. She has a medical history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, hypothyroidism, and atrial fibrillation. Her medications include metformin, levothyroxine, and apixaban. She follows a strict vegan diet and drinks two glasses of wine daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 28 kg/m\u00b2. Neurological examination reveals reduced vibration sense and proprioception in both feet with absent ankle reflexes. Blood tests reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 102 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean cell volume 105 fL (80-98)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count 6.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count 220 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal vitamin B12 185 pmol/L (150-700)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFolate 18 nmol/L (\u003E7)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 85 \u03bcg/L (15-200)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone 2.8 mIU/L (0.4-4.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methylmalonic acid level","Active B12 level","Intrinsic factor antibodies","Homocysteine level","Schilling test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with macrocytic anaemia, neurological symptoms suggestive of peripheral neuropathy, and a borderline low total vitamin B12 level of 185 pmol/L. The combination of a vegan diet, neurological findings, and macrocytosis strongly suggests B12 deficiency, but the total B12 level falls within the grey zone, where functional deficiency cannot be excluded.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive B12 level\u003C/strong\u003E (holotranscobalamin) is the most appropriate next investigation. Active B12 measures the fraction of vitamin B12 bound to transcobalamin II, which represents the metabolically available B12 that can be delivered to tissues. This test is particularly valuable when total B12 levels are borderline (typically 150-300 pmol/L), as approximately 80% of measured total B12 is bound to haptocorrin and metabolically inactive. Active B12 provides a more accurate assessment of B12 status and is often added on as reflex testing by the laboratories in situations such as this case. As per recent amendments to the Medicare Benefits Schedule (MBS), from 1 July 2025, Medicare will fund both total vitamin B12 and holotranscobalamin as an initial test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethylmalonic acid level\u003C/strong\u003E is a functional marker that accumulates when there is insufficient B12 for cellular metabolism. As per the recent MBS update, where the initial vitamin B12 result is abnormal or inconclusive or homocysteine or methylmalonic acid testing can be performed next. Given that active B12 testing has not yet been performed in this patient with borderline total B12, it represents the logical next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrinsic factor antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E would help identify pernicious anaemia as the cause of B12 deficiency. However, confirming the presence of B12 deficiency should precede investigation of its aetiology. Additionally, this patient\u0027s vegan diet provides a clear risk factor for dietary B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomocysteine level\u003C/strong\u003E can be elevated in both B12 and folate deficiency. Given this patient\u0027s normal folate level, an elevated homocysteine would support B12 deficiency. However, homocysteine is less specific than active B12 or methylmalonic acid, as it can also be elevated in renal impairment and with certain medications. As per the recent MBS update, where the initial vitamin B12 result is  abnormal or inconclusive, homocysteine or methylmalonic acid testing can be performed next\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESchilling test\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used to differentiate between dietary B12 deficiency and malabsorption due to intrinsic factor deficiency. This test involved administering radiolabelled B12 orally and measuring urinary excretion. However, the Schilling test is now obsolete and no longer available in clinical practice due to the unavailability of radiolabelled cobalamin, complexity of the test procedure, and the development of more practical alternatives. Modern practice relies on serum markers and antibody testing to investigate the cause of B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Holotranscobalamin (active B12) is now recommended as a first-line test alongside total B12 for detecting vitamin B12 deficiency.","When total B12 levels are borderline (150-300 pmol/L), active B12 testing provides better assessment of metabolically available B12."],"references":["Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. Amendments to Medicare Benefits Schedule (MBS) for Vitamin B12 testing [Internet]. Canberra (AU): Department of Health and Aged Care; 2025 Jun 3 [cited 2025 Jul 6]. Available from: https://www.mbsonline.gov.au/internet/mbsonline/publishing.nsf/650f3eec0dfb990fca25692100069854/d43378b744efcbe2ca258c65001e3205/$FILE/PDF%20Version%20-%20Amendments%20to%20Medicare%20Benefits%20Schedule%20for%20Vitamin%20B12%20testing.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1270"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-06T09:04:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-06T09:06:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1270"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108076"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":